Vietnam War on the institution. The authors describe how the medical school built itself back up after nearing the brink of financial ruin in the late 1970s, with philanthropic support and a renewal of its longstanding commitments to biomedical innovation and discovery. Central to this story is the closely intertwined, and at times tumultuous, relationship between Weill Cornell and its hospital affiliate, now known as New York–Presbyterian. Today the medical school’s reach extends from its home base in Manhattan to a branch campus in Qatar and to partnerships with institutions in Houston, Tanzania, and Haiti. As Weill Cornell Medicine relates, the medical college has never been better poised to improve health around the globe than it is now.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aMedical collegeszNew York (State)xHistory. 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 4aEducation & History Of Education. 4aNew York History.  aWeill Cornell Medicine, Cornell University Medical College, Weill Cornell Medical College, history, medical school, global health.1 aGlimcher, Laurie H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoon, Jennifer, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2016z9783110485295oZDB-23-DPM40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170367640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501703676423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501703676/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL